WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.200
So yeah, we'll have our first keynote.

00:00:06.200 --> 00:00:11.680
So Isabel Zimmerman is a senior software engineer at Posit and a major contributor to open source

00:00:11.680 --> 00:00:13.360
and champion of open source.

00:00:13.360 --> 00:00:15.680
We're really lucky and excited to have her.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:19.600
So Isabel, let's have a round of applause.

00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:21.040
I did data science for a while.

00:00:21.040 --> 00:00:28.120
I transitioned into doing data science tool making because I just really love tools.

00:00:28.120 --> 00:00:33.840
I was actually the first full-time Python open source hire at Posit.

00:00:33.840 --> 00:00:36.959
And this was at a time where this company was still called RStudio.

00:00:36.959 --> 00:00:42.560
We actually already had people who were building Python stuff, but I was the first person who

00:00:42.560 --> 00:00:47.560
was dedicated full-time for solely novel open source Python work.

00:00:47.560 --> 00:00:52.919
I started out building MLOps packages, but nowadays I'm spending most of my time building

00:00:52.919 --> 00:00:55.360
the Python experience in different IDEs.

00:00:56.240 --> 00:01:01.279
And I have to say, my love of tools is not really constrained just to computers.

00:01:01.279 --> 00:01:05.959
If you haven't noticed, there's a giant magical goose on this slide.

00:01:05.959 --> 00:01:07.720
I am a huge fantasy reader.

00:01:07.720 --> 00:01:14.199
I'm actually flying to Boston from Salt Lake City, Utah for a fantasy conference.

00:01:14.199 --> 00:01:19.239
And one of my favorite fantasy books, there's this magical earring, no spoilers, but there's

00:01:19.239 --> 00:01:22.879
this magical earring that's passed down from generation to generation.

00:01:23.480 --> 00:01:28.239
And it turns out that this small little thing can beat the big evil bad guy at the end of

00:01:28.239 --> 00:01:29.239
the book.

00:01:29.239 --> 00:01:33.519
And I think there's something really special about having something in hand, even if it

00:01:33.519 --> 00:01:40.199
doesn't feel like the craziest, most magical tool, that can help solve a problem.

00:01:40.199 --> 00:01:44.959
And so I assume you're here not to hear about my favorite fantasy books, but probably because

00:01:44.959 --> 00:01:51.559
you are either a Python user or someone who uses and loves data or some Venn diagram overlap

00:01:51.559 --> 00:01:53.839
of these two.

00:01:53.839 --> 00:01:59.279
And maybe you're thinking, why do I even care about the tools I use?

00:01:59.279 --> 00:02:01.160
This is a whole talk about them.

00:02:01.160 --> 00:02:03.839
Why dedicate all of this time and energy?

00:02:03.839 --> 00:02:10.759
And so just off the bat, I consider a tool anything that you can use to carry out a particular

00:02:10.759 --> 00:02:13.039
function.

00:02:13.039 --> 00:02:15.880
This talk is about tool users and tool builders.

00:02:15.880 --> 00:02:20.399
And maybe you identify with one of these identities more than the other.

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:21.759
And they're not mutually exclusive.

00:02:21.759 --> 00:02:27.679
But if you think about caring about using tools, maybe you feel more strongly about

00:02:27.679 --> 00:02:28.679
this identity.

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:31.919
You know, I'm someone who consumes these things.

00:02:31.919 --> 00:02:37.800
If we think of this as like some sort of fantasy story, the villain in our tool user persona

00:02:37.800 --> 00:02:43.440
would be the inertia of only using the tools that you already know, because, you know,

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:44.440
it's easier.

00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:46.119
You already know them.

00:02:46.119 --> 00:02:52.839
And so I'd like to consider that using tools and picking tools thoughtfully is very important.

00:02:52.839 --> 00:02:56.899
And choosing the right one will make your life way easier.

00:02:56.899 --> 00:03:02.800
So I'm someone who probably like most of you, when you get out into this data science world,

00:03:02.800 --> 00:03:05.000
you start using something called Pandas.

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.360
And this is a data frame library that, you know, it's what I was taught in school.

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:13.479
It's like one of the most popular libraries out there for Python.

00:03:13.479 --> 00:03:15.440
And I thought it was a great place to start.

00:03:15.440 --> 00:03:18.279
And it served me very well for a long time.

00:03:18.279 --> 00:03:20.919
The data I was working with started to get bigger.

00:03:20.919 --> 00:03:24.720
And Pandas started to feel a little bit slower, a little bit clunkier.

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:28.199
So I ended up changing over to something called Pollers.

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:30.479
The syntax is very similar.

00:03:30.479 --> 00:03:31.479
But it's built on Rust.

00:03:31.479 --> 00:03:33.479
And it's a little bit faster.

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:34.479
And this was a simple switch.

00:03:34.479 --> 00:03:37.220
You know, a lot of the API is the same.

00:03:37.220 --> 00:03:42.559
But it made my life feel a little bit faster.

00:03:42.559 --> 00:03:47.800
And everyone sits somewhere on the spectrum of like building and using tools.

00:03:47.800 --> 00:03:51.759
And maybe you don't identify immediately as somebody who is building tools.

00:03:51.759 --> 00:03:54.160
But I'd like to convince you otherwise.

00:03:54.160 --> 00:03:58.699
One, I think it's important for everyone to even think of themselves as like a little

00:03:58.699 --> 00:04:00.600
bit of a tool builder.

00:04:00.600 --> 00:04:04.360
By building a tool for yourself, you can speed up your own work.

00:04:04.360 --> 00:04:08.679
And speed up not only your work today, but your work for future you.

00:04:08.679 --> 00:04:12.440
The barrier to building a tool has never been lower with the help of AI.

00:04:12.440 --> 00:04:17.760
You know, your cloud, your copilot, your chat GPT is able to help you build Python packages

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:21.079
if you don't know where to start.

00:04:21.079 --> 00:04:25.040
And this tool doesn't have to be something that's widely shared into the world.

00:04:25.040 --> 00:04:29.640
It can be something that's just for yourself.

00:04:29.640 --> 00:04:36.119
As part of my own personal book nerdiness, I actually rebind books as well.

00:04:36.119 --> 00:04:40.799
And I have to do specific measurements for like the cover, the back, the spine, and all

00:04:40.799 --> 00:04:43.359
of these little hinges in between.

00:04:43.359 --> 00:04:47.720
And I like a very specific like 7 millimeter gutter.

00:04:47.720 --> 00:04:50.959
And all of the tools out there are all 5 millimeter.

00:04:50.959 --> 00:04:57.160
So I made this silly little like literal piece of plastic to help me make my own books.

00:04:57.160 --> 00:04:59.559
It's something only I will ever use.

00:04:59.559 --> 00:05:00.880
But it helps me every day.

00:05:00.880 --> 00:05:02.239
Well, maybe not every day.

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:08.559
Every day I'm doing hobbies to make these books better.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:10.920
So your tools don't have to be anything fancy.

00:05:10.920 --> 00:05:14.119
And also you might already be building them.

00:05:14.119 --> 00:05:18.519
Maybe you're someone like me who is fat fingering Git push all the time.

00:05:18.519 --> 00:05:22.920
And now has an alias on their computer so that when you write GTI push, it actually

00:05:22.920 --> 00:05:25.920
uses Git instead.

00:05:25.920 --> 00:05:29.640
You know, if you're writing code, you're building something.

00:05:29.880 --> 00:05:32.959
A dashboard or a report, that's a tool.

00:05:32.959 --> 00:05:36.040
It's a tool used to make business decisions.

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:40.760
Maybe you have a function that you've been slacking back and forth with your co-workers.

00:05:40.760 --> 00:05:45.720
That's a tool that you've been helping streamline your data workflows.

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:47.600
Or maybe something else entirely.

00:05:47.600 --> 00:05:51.760
So these are all tools you might already be making.

00:05:51.760 --> 00:05:56.559
And when I transitioned from like a data scientist persona to a tool builder persona,

00:05:56.559 --> 00:05:59.880
I thought that I knew what mattered.

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:01.799
I had already filled my bag with lots of tools.

00:06:01.799 --> 00:06:04.200
You know, I could write clean code.

00:06:04.200 --> 00:06:05.600
I could design APIs.

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:07.839
I knew how to optimize performance.

00:06:07.839 --> 00:06:13.799
And I thought, you know, if my code works, people will use it.

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:18.119
And we actually do a fair amount of user testing at Posit, where we will watch

00:06:18.119 --> 00:06:19.559
someone use tools.

00:06:19.559 --> 00:06:24.679
And I have watched truly like the most brilliant people that I look up to so

00:06:24.679 --> 00:06:29.920
much get confused about a tool because a button is in the wrong spot.

00:06:29.920 --> 00:06:34.880
Or, you know, you press refresh and it only refreshes like the first layer of your

00:06:34.880 --> 00:06:37.359
namespace and not the whole namespace.

00:06:37.359 --> 00:06:39.359
Or just something.

00:06:39.359 --> 00:06:41.000
And people get stuck.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:42.279
That's a part of life.

00:06:42.279 --> 00:06:46.399
Tools are imperfect because they're built by imperfect people and you are an

00:06:46.399 --> 00:06:47.519
imperfect user.

00:06:47.519 --> 00:06:51.399
And I think that is like the most beautiful thing to think about.

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:55.519
Because if we are both imperfect on kind of both sides of this coin, that means

00:06:55.519 --> 00:07:02.160
that there are skills there that we can build and that we can learn.

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:07.160
So, if you're like writing your resume, we often think about things in the scale

00:07:07.160 --> 00:07:11.640
of like there's hard skills and then there's soft skills.

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:15.839
You know, hard skills are things like I know how to use scikit-learn.

00:07:15.839 --> 00:07:17.239
I write C++ code.

00:07:17.239 --> 00:07:20.920
And soft skills are like I can lead a team or I'm really good at writing

00:07:20.920 --> 00:07:22.600
documentation.

00:07:22.600 --> 00:07:25.559
And there is a lot of baggage around these terms that I want to address.

00:07:25.559 --> 00:07:28.799
You know, LinkedIn, it feels like, swaps every year.

00:07:28.799 --> 00:07:31.320
Half the time they say, all you need are hard skills.

00:07:31.320 --> 00:07:32.720
We don't care about soft skills anymore.

00:07:32.720 --> 00:07:34.519
And then it's all you need are soft skills.

00:07:34.519 --> 00:07:36.000
We don't care about hard skills anymore.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:40.320
And I'm not interested today in like really convincing you of one or the other.

00:07:40.320 --> 00:07:46.000
But more thinking about this dichotomy of the ways that we're working.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:49.640
And when I was thinking about this talk and like how to talk about tools,

00:07:49.640 --> 00:07:53.799
I realized that tools have these same hard and soft skills.

00:07:53.799 --> 00:07:56.799
So your hard skills and tools are these computer elements.

00:07:56.799 --> 00:08:01.279
Things like modularity, reproducibility, flexibility.

00:08:01.279 --> 00:08:05.160
Whereas the soft skills are more of these human elements of your tools.

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:09.079
Things like knowing your user, understanding their needs,

00:08:09.079 --> 00:08:13.399
delighting in the small things, and explaining your work.

00:08:13.399 --> 00:08:14.239
And here's the thing.

00:08:14.239 --> 00:08:20.079
Your tools, to be really delightful tools that people love to use,

00:08:20.079 --> 00:08:23.359
have to have both these hard skills and the soft ones.

00:08:26.239 --> 00:08:30.600
All right, so we'll start with what a tool's hard skills are.

00:08:30.600 --> 00:08:33.200
With modularity.

00:08:33.200 --> 00:08:35.119
So when you're building a tool, a lot of times

00:08:35.119 --> 00:08:39.039
the first thing you have to think of is like, where are we starting from?

00:08:39.039 --> 00:08:42.359
And one of the first Python packages I was building is called Vediver.

00:08:42.359 --> 00:08:44.119
And it's an MLOps framework.

00:08:44.119 --> 00:08:47.520
And there's this element of building APIs.

00:08:47.520 --> 00:08:51.640
And I had to decide, where are these APIs coming from?

00:08:51.640 --> 00:08:55.320
I could, of course, go spend all this time, research,

00:08:55.320 --> 00:08:58.159
build out my own REST API generation.

00:08:58.159 --> 00:09:02.479
But I realized there's so many fantastic community tools out there

00:09:02.479 --> 00:09:06.200
that I can leverage what's already been built in the open source community

00:09:06.200 --> 00:09:11.640
and be able to have this relentless focus on the MLOps side of the work.

00:09:11.640 --> 00:09:15.479
So for tool builders, finding tools that work with what you already know

00:09:15.479 --> 00:09:16.840
is super important.

00:09:16.840 --> 00:09:19.320
And as a user, it's also really important

00:09:19.320 --> 00:09:23.080
to maybe understand what your tools are being built off of,

00:09:23.080 --> 00:09:27.000
to have these clear extension points.

00:09:27.000 --> 00:09:29.559
Tomorrow morning, one of my colleagues, Jules,

00:09:29.559 --> 00:09:33.919
is going to be giving a talk about how to build an extension package

00:09:33.919 --> 00:09:36.479
for different Python packages.

00:09:36.479 --> 00:09:40.679
I would love for 2026 to be like the year of Python extension packages.

00:09:40.679 --> 00:09:46.200
I want to see everyone making specialized tools for what they know.

00:09:46.200 --> 00:09:52.200
Because it makes your life a lot easier when something works exactly for you.

00:09:52.200 --> 00:09:56.840
The other good thing about modularity is, if we think about LEGOs,

00:09:56.840 --> 00:09:58.559
you can connect them to themselves.

00:09:58.559 --> 00:10:00.799
So if you're building on a modular surface,

00:10:00.799 --> 00:10:04.479
you're able to have a tool that grows with your user.

00:10:04.479 --> 00:10:07.359
Like in the Vetiver case, I can think of,

00:10:07.359 --> 00:10:10.520
you can do all these cool things with models, like what I've added.

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:13.520
But you're also able to make really complex APIs

00:10:13.520 --> 00:10:17.520
because of the basics of FastAPI.

00:10:17.520 --> 00:10:19.280
OK, so this is a talk about tools.

00:10:19.280 --> 00:10:21.719
And it's only fair for me to eventually introduce the tool

00:10:21.719 --> 00:10:23.599
that I spend most of my day job on.

00:10:23.599 --> 00:10:26.159
And that's an IDE called Positron.

00:10:26.159 --> 00:10:30.000
So Positron is an IDE built specifically for data science.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:34.799
And if you're a VS Code user, it might look a little bit familiar.

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:36.200
It is a VS Code fork.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:42.280
And it has different elements, like this Variables pane, this Plots pane,

00:10:42.280 --> 00:10:46.440
including a film strip on the side, and this built-in console,

00:10:46.440 --> 00:10:52.200
along with many other goodies that we've added to help emphasize this data

00:10:52.200 --> 00:10:54.919
science experience.

00:10:54.919 --> 00:11:01.559
But we built off of the basics of Code OSS, which is this open source VS Code.

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:05.080
And it's useful for us because we are able to, again,

00:11:05.080 --> 00:11:08.520
have this relentless focus on the data science experience.

00:11:08.520 --> 00:11:10.919
But also, it's helpful for users because they

00:11:10.919 --> 00:11:18.679
can plug into this huge ecosystem of OpenVSX and VS Code extensions.

00:11:18.679 --> 00:11:20.840
Something that we've gotten for free because of this

00:11:20.840 --> 00:11:25.000
is the idea of growing and outgrowing your laptop through Remote SSH.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:26.679
And another one of my colleagues tomorrow

00:11:26.679 --> 00:11:32.119
is going to be giving a talk on Positron and Remote SSH.

00:11:32.119 --> 00:11:36.440
It's Rodrigo's talk tomorrow, I think, at 9 AM or 11.

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:37.479
I'm so sorry.

00:11:37.479 --> 00:11:40.039
One of those two.

00:11:40.039 --> 00:11:45.760
So alongside reproducibility, alongside of modularity,

00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:47.960
we also want reproducibility.

00:11:47.960 --> 00:11:51.039
And data science folks know all about reproducibility.

00:11:51.039 --> 00:11:55.039
We think about it and how it is the foundational thing

00:11:55.039 --> 00:11:58.359
for trustworthy science.

00:11:58.359 --> 00:12:03.760
There's a strong pull for exploring data in reproducible ways.

00:12:03.760 --> 00:12:05.880
But there's also this tension because there's

00:12:05.880 --> 00:12:09.400
a lot of really cool ways to explore data with a GUI, where

00:12:09.400 --> 00:12:12.239
I'm going to load the CSV, and I'm going to click around.

00:12:12.239 --> 00:12:13.840
And it's a little bit of a mismatch.

00:12:16.559 --> 00:12:19.760
We can think about when we're doing data science

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:22.359
or when we're doing data work, where are we

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:26.200
doing steps that are not reproducible?

00:12:26.200 --> 00:12:29.679
Maybe you're loading your data from a CSV in Pandas.

00:12:29.679 --> 00:12:31.520
You're doing some exploration.

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:35.239
And then you're exporting it to Excel and making a table there.

00:12:35.239 --> 00:12:37.359
I would encourage you to think about this workflow,

00:12:37.359 --> 00:12:40.640
the places where, when you tell your colleagues about it,

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.280
it's, OK, download this, and then click, and then click, and then click.

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:48.280
Because those are things that are going to be less reproducible over time.

00:12:48.280 --> 00:12:50.760
There's an open source package called Great Tables

00:12:50.760 --> 00:12:56.679
that allows you to move directly from building your data exploration with

00:12:56.679 --> 00:12:59.880
Pandas or Pollers right into a table, or if you

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:02.679
want to use plots or something like that.

00:13:02.679 --> 00:13:06.599
So thinking really about completing your whole cycle in Python

00:13:06.599 --> 00:13:09.679
or in some sort of language where you can pass this off

00:13:09.679 --> 00:13:13.400
as a reproducible artifact, rather than saying,

00:13:13.400 --> 00:13:17.440
OK, here are all of the steps to click all of the right buttons

00:13:17.440 --> 00:13:18.900
to get your data in the right place.

00:13:21.239 --> 00:13:23.960
In Positron, there's something called a Data Explorer.

00:13:23.960 --> 00:13:28.080
And when we first built it, there was a little bit of this trap of,

00:13:28.080 --> 00:13:29.359
look at how beautiful this is.

00:13:29.359 --> 00:13:31.979
It can handle millions of rows, millions of columns.

00:13:31.979 --> 00:13:33.559
You can add filters.

00:13:33.559 --> 00:13:35.960
Here, I'm looking at different literary prizes.

00:13:35.960 --> 00:13:39.119
I want to look at Booker Prize winners.

00:13:39.119 --> 00:13:44.000
I'm able to look at my data in ascending or descending order.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.400
It's a great place to do quick data exploration.

00:13:47.400 --> 00:13:50.780
But if you notice, it's a lot of, if I was telling a colleague,

00:13:50.780 --> 00:13:53.440
I would say, add this filter, add this filter.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:56.200
So we added this button where you can convert to code,

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:01.359
where because all of these filters are built in a very modular way,

00:14:01.359 --> 00:14:05.900
it has a one-to-one balance of, I can click this button because I

00:14:05.900 --> 00:14:07.200
know what the filters are.

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:11.880
I can generate code, not using AI, just using a tree

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:14.919
to have code that works and runs and generates the same data

00:14:14.919 --> 00:14:17.559
exploration every single time.

00:14:17.559 --> 00:14:19.919
So I think this is a really interesting way to bridge

00:14:19.919 --> 00:14:24.520
the gap between GUI exploration and having a reproducible output.

00:14:27.400 --> 00:14:30.280
And flexibility, when I think of flexibility,

00:14:30.280 --> 00:14:33.559
I think of a Swiss army knife, perhaps, in tools.

00:14:33.559 --> 00:14:36.880
So it's convenient.

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:40.799
Swiss army knife, you can have scissors and a bottle opener

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:44.440
and a knife or whatever else you need for your little tasks

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:46.799
to open the boxes.

00:14:46.799 --> 00:14:50.919
And I'm pro-Swiss army knife, but you're not

00:14:50.919 --> 00:14:53.520
going to use a Swiss army knife to build a house.

00:14:53.520 --> 00:14:56.059
So you have to think about what kind of flexibility

00:14:56.059 --> 00:14:59.479
works well in the projects that you're building.

00:14:59.479 --> 00:15:02.320
And if you're not aware, there's something called the Zen of Python.

00:15:02.320 --> 00:15:05.960
If you type import this, it will print it out.

00:15:05.960 --> 00:15:10.520
And it has these core values of how to use Python as a language.

00:15:10.520 --> 00:15:12.599
And one of the ones that's really interesting to me

00:15:12.599 --> 00:15:14.880
is that simple is better than complex.

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:18.159
Complex is better than complicated.

00:15:18.159 --> 00:15:20.159
And I know that this slide says flexibility,

00:15:20.159 --> 00:15:22.119
and I really do want to encourage that.

00:15:22.119 --> 00:15:24.840
But I also want people to think really thoughtfully

00:15:24.840 --> 00:15:28.640
about the kind of information that they're ingesting

00:15:28.640 --> 00:15:32.359
in terms of when you're writing functions or something like that.

00:15:32.359 --> 00:15:36.200
Lucas Lange, there's a PyCon keynote from 2022.

00:15:36.200 --> 00:15:40.599
I highly recommend it if you ever write any types in your code.

00:15:40.599 --> 00:15:45.280
And he really talks about a function that has insane types

00:15:45.280 --> 00:15:48.520
is probably a code smell of you need to break this down and make

00:15:48.520 --> 00:15:51.440
your code slightly less flexible.

00:15:51.440 --> 00:15:53.280
And I did fall into this trap.

00:15:53.280 --> 00:15:55.919
When I was starting to build tools, I would write a function,

00:15:55.919 --> 00:15:58.599
and I would type it, and I would see these crazy unions

00:15:58.599 --> 00:16:02.320
where I'm supporting polar's data frames, and panda's data frames,

00:16:02.320 --> 00:16:05.799
and lists, and dictionaries, and tuples, and all of it,

00:16:05.799 --> 00:16:07.960
when I really should have focused on building

00:16:07.960 --> 00:16:10.599
modular things for each function,

00:16:10.599 --> 00:16:14.280
and then combining them in a more clever way.

00:16:14.280 --> 00:16:18.000
Because if you have something that accepts really complex inputs,

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:23.919
it's going to be way harder to also support very complex tasks.

00:16:23.919 --> 00:16:27.599
I think the rise of AI tools recently has highlighted the importance

00:16:27.599 --> 00:16:30.359
of starting with a reasonable amount of context,

00:16:30.359 --> 00:16:34.799
and then letting users configure more or less information.

00:16:34.799 --> 00:16:36.799
Something that we've noticed is like AI often

00:16:36.799 --> 00:16:40.400
does not have all of the right context for data science work.

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:42.640
If it's only doing static analysis, it only

00:16:42.640 --> 00:16:45.880
knows that there is some sort of data frame called data,

00:16:45.880 --> 00:16:48.919
and it's getting this information from this URL.

00:16:48.919 --> 00:16:52.280
So in Positron, there's this thing called Positron Assistant,

00:16:52.280 --> 00:16:55.479
and it gives the LLMs a little bit of your data.

00:16:55.479 --> 00:16:59.159
It gives them images from your plots and whatever else

00:16:59.159 --> 00:17:04.400
you want in order to get the most out of AI for your data experience.

00:17:04.400 --> 00:17:06.359
This kind of has like this happy path, or we

00:17:06.400 --> 00:17:08.439
think of it as like a pit of success.

00:17:08.439 --> 00:17:11.160
So if you just open this up, it will have the context

00:17:11.160 --> 00:17:16.880
that's important for your model to make better information for a better output.

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:20.479
But also, we care about privacy, so we need a really clear way

00:17:20.479 --> 00:17:22.520
to add and remove context.

00:17:22.520 --> 00:17:25.880
So you can see I'm clicking this eye, open and closed.

00:17:25.880 --> 00:17:29.920
So say you can see this information, you can't see this information,

00:17:29.920 --> 00:17:33.920
or adding in different context.

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:40.079
These are what I think of as the hard skills, hard skills of a tool.

00:17:40.079 --> 00:17:42.160
And there is one thing that is front of mind

00:17:42.160 --> 00:17:44.560
that I've touched on very briefly, but that

00:17:44.560 --> 00:17:51.479
is the fact that AI 2025 is the era of AI everything.

00:17:51.479 --> 00:17:54.319
If you're writing code these days and it's out in the world,

00:17:54.319 --> 00:17:56.359
it will probably be read by AI assistants,

00:17:56.359 --> 00:18:01.079
or perhaps it's being read by Amazon Bedrock, by your local models

00:18:01.079 --> 00:18:02.640
or whatever.

00:18:02.640 --> 00:18:05.920
And AI is really good at these strong skills.

00:18:05.920 --> 00:18:10.119
You can almost use them as keywords to get better output from your LLM.

00:18:10.119 --> 00:18:15.079
Make this function more flexible, make this function more modular.

00:18:15.079 --> 00:18:19.479
But what AI does really struggle with, even with the right context,

00:18:19.479 --> 00:18:24.199
is what users actually need, or these soft skills.

00:18:24.199 --> 00:18:29.040
So great tools require technical excellence, but also user empathy.

00:18:29.040 --> 00:18:32.560
And I was looking at the Stack Overflow survey.

00:18:32.560 --> 00:18:35.400
There's 25,000 responses.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:40.000
And these are things that people do not plan to use AI ever for this task.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:43.359
And it looks like developers are showing the most resistance

00:18:43.359 --> 00:18:46.400
to these high-responsibility systemic tasks,

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:48.119
like deployment and monitoring.

00:18:48.119 --> 00:18:51.520
But also really interesting is project planning.

00:18:51.520 --> 00:18:55.880
And I think part of project planning, in my mind, my hypothesis,

00:18:55.880 --> 00:18:59.079
is that project planning is a lot of the soft skills.

00:18:59.079 --> 00:19:02.439
Project planning is realizing my stakeholders

00:19:02.439 --> 00:19:03.880
need this output.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:08.439
My stakeholders think this is important, or I think this is important.

00:19:08.439 --> 00:19:13.839
Or that product knowledge that you carry with yourself and with your team,

00:19:13.839 --> 00:19:22.239
kind of these soft skills that AI is not able to take over for us.

00:19:22.239 --> 00:19:24.520
So when we think about the soft skills, I really

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:28.479
want people to think about the human side of a tool.

00:19:28.479 --> 00:19:30.920
And the first thing is to know your users.

00:19:34.079 --> 00:19:36.479
At Posit, a lot of us were data scientists.

00:19:36.479 --> 00:19:38.959
So we have a lot of data science knowledge.

00:19:38.959 --> 00:19:44.880
So we really intimately know the struggles of what we were running into.

00:19:44.880 --> 00:19:47.119
And I think something interesting here is

00:19:47.119 --> 00:19:50.160
the difference between a data scientist and a software engineer.

00:19:50.160 --> 00:19:53.760
Data work inherently looks a little bit different

00:19:53.760 --> 00:19:56.280
than what we would consider software engineer work.

00:19:56.280 --> 00:20:01.959
Data practitioners are more on exploring uncharted territories.

00:20:01.959 --> 00:20:06.079
They do a lot of iteration and a lot of experimentation.

00:20:06.079 --> 00:20:09.880
And then software engineers, we can think of them as building castles

00:20:09.880 --> 00:20:14.520
in known lands, things that involve a lot of structure,

00:20:14.520 --> 00:20:18.040
and things that have a very specific outcome.

00:20:18.040 --> 00:20:22.079
So you're not going to give your cartographer a mason's tools.

00:20:22.079 --> 00:20:24.560
So knowing your users is really important.

00:20:24.560 --> 00:20:26.800
And if you don't know, it's OK to ask.

00:20:26.800 --> 00:20:30.800
I think that's a very thoughtful way to approach this problem.

00:20:33.319 --> 00:20:37.079
For us, we realize that a tool that's built for software engineers

00:20:37.079 --> 00:20:41.920
might not be the best fit for someone who needs to do a lot of experimentation.

00:20:41.920 --> 00:20:47.000
And one way we really wanted to show data scientists that we understand

00:20:47.000 --> 00:20:50.000
their struggles and something that I use almost daily

00:20:50.000 --> 00:20:53.520
is having a permanent console available in Positron.

00:20:53.520 --> 00:20:57.599
So if you're not familiar with having some sort of iPython console,

00:20:57.599 --> 00:21:01.959
you can think of it as sort of a Jupyter Notebook light that's built in,

00:21:01.959 --> 00:21:08.719
that's always on, that's activated all the time available in your IDE.

00:21:08.719 --> 00:21:14.000
So in this little GIF, I'm just mashing Command-Enter all the way down.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:16.520
If I was on Windows, it would be Control-Enter.

00:21:16.520 --> 00:21:19.479
And you can see I can run this line by line.

00:21:19.479 --> 00:21:25.400
This plot is slowly getting built up as I'm executing different pieces of it.

00:21:25.400 --> 00:21:28.920
And it's really built for this quick experimentation.

00:21:28.920 --> 00:21:31.839
I'm also able to go down there and type in this console.

00:21:31.839 --> 00:21:35.040
And it's fully syntax highlighted.

00:21:35.040 --> 00:21:37.439
You're able to get code completions there.

00:21:37.439 --> 00:21:42.040
And we've actually made changes to the LSP, or Language Server Protocol,

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:46.760
inside the IDE so that it's optimized for data science use.

00:21:46.760 --> 00:21:49.680
This is all things that we realize data scientists,

00:21:49.680 --> 00:21:54.719
if they're using a data frame and they have either a period or your brackets,

00:21:54.719 --> 00:21:57.359
they probably will want a column.

00:21:57.359 --> 00:22:02.280
So we focused on making sure column completions come to the front.

00:22:02.280 --> 00:22:05.040
And just these little things that really show

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:09.560
that we know how data scientists work because a lot of us

00:22:09.560 --> 00:22:11.920
are data scientists or were data scientists.

00:22:12.920 --> 00:22:15.719
And discoverability is a lot of this work.

00:22:15.719 --> 00:22:18.520
So when you're thinking about sharing a report

00:22:18.520 --> 00:22:23.719
or thinking about building a tool, you want to really be this little goose

00:22:23.719 --> 00:22:27.800
that's shining your lantern on the path that should be traveled the most.

00:22:27.800 --> 00:22:31.239
This is really kind of a subset of knowing your user.

00:22:31.239 --> 00:22:34.199
And all of these soft skills really come from a place of empathy

00:22:34.199 --> 00:22:37.000
for the people who are using the tools that you're building,

00:22:37.000 --> 00:22:40.800
or thinking about how you want your tool to be used.

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:45.959
How you want your tool to support you as you're using it.

00:22:45.959 --> 00:22:51.520
So for discoverability, we ought to think about what will users care about?

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:58.640
And how can we help them find things that are not immediately obvious?

00:22:58.640 --> 00:23:01.880
Discoverability really is an eternal quest.

00:23:01.880 --> 00:23:06.400
Your hidden features are going to be like secret passages.

00:23:06.400 --> 00:23:08.719
Just because there's treasure at the end of this tunnel,

00:23:08.719 --> 00:23:13.719
if nobody knows it's there, nobody's going to find it.

00:23:13.719 --> 00:23:18.680
So discoverability is really hard in documentation, in the actual API,

00:23:18.680 --> 00:23:22.640
in the UI of an app that you might be deploying.

00:23:22.640 --> 00:23:25.920
Documentation is really helpful, but it's also equally important

00:23:25.920 --> 00:23:28.640
to have things that are self-documenting.

00:23:28.640 --> 00:23:31.319
So when you're using a tool, we want to think about,

00:23:31.319 --> 00:23:33.959
are things easy for me to remember so I'm not

00:23:33.959 --> 00:23:37.199
looking at the docs every single time?

00:23:37.199 --> 00:23:40.479
Information can be hard to find and retain,

00:23:40.479 --> 00:23:43.479
so bringing to the front of what actually gets used is super important.

00:23:46.479 --> 00:23:48.280
So we want to think about, what are things

00:23:48.280 --> 00:23:53.839
that are high impact but hard to find, or things that are constantly used?

00:23:53.839 --> 00:23:59.719
There's a project called Quarto that is a open source publishing and authoring

00:23:59.719 --> 00:24:00.680
platform.

00:24:00.680 --> 00:24:03.119
It's actually how I've built all of my slides.

00:24:03.119 --> 00:24:05.400
It's how I've built my website.

00:24:05.400 --> 00:24:07.040
You can build dashboards with it.

00:24:07.880 --> 00:24:11.760
You can integrate it with different applications, like Shiny.

00:24:11.760 --> 00:24:13.880
And it's a really beautiful tool that we

00:24:13.880 --> 00:24:18.119
wanted people to have a great authoring experience in Positron with.

00:24:18.119 --> 00:24:22.719
So here you can see that it looks like just a markdown file

00:24:22.719 --> 00:24:25.079
that you're also able to run code in.

00:24:25.079 --> 00:24:28.040
I honestly, I could give a whole nother talk about how much I love Quarto.

00:24:28.040 --> 00:24:31.880
It is one of my favorite things to use.

00:24:31.880 --> 00:24:35.479
But there's a lot of settings, and there's a lot of ways to use Quarto.

00:24:35.479 --> 00:24:38.119
And when I'm building out something like these slides,

00:24:38.119 --> 00:24:41.439
a lot of times I'm making changes, and then I'm pressing Save.

00:24:41.439 --> 00:24:43.280
And I'll make changes, and I'm pressing Save.

00:24:43.280 --> 00:24:46.199
And when you're rendering these slides locally,

00:24:46.199 --> 00:24:50.959
that is kind of annoying to bring down my whole little local host

00:24:50.959 --> 00:24:52.800
and restart it.

00:24:52.800 --> 00:24:55.079
So we have this editor action bar where you

00:24:55.079 --> 00:24:57.520
can see there's this preview, this render on save.

00:24:57.520 --> 00:25:02.400
You can toggle between source and visual, insert a code cell.

00:25:02.400 --> 00:25:07.119
We wanted to think about what is important for users.

00:25:07.119 --> 00:25:08.920
If you're using something like this, you're

00:25:08.920 --> 00:25:11.160
probably wanting to run code in markdown.

00:25:11.160 --> 00:25:13.880
So we're going to have a button to insert a code cell.

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:17.880
We also want to elevate the setting of render on save.

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:20.560
It's not the biggest feature.

00:25:20.560 --> 00:25:25.199
People aren't going to Positron saying, wow, I can render on save now.

00:25:25.199 --> 00:25:27.599
But being able to elevate this because we

00:25:27.599 --> 00:25:32.760
think it's important for users for their own workflow.

00:25:32.760 --> 00:25:36.920
We're also making different UI changes to how our Jupyter notebooks look

00:25:36.920 --> 00:25:43.239
and to help ease discovery and have our Jupyter notebook experience

00:25:43.239 --> 00:25:44.479
feel good for you.

00:25:44.479 --> 00:25:46.560
So if you have big opinions on Jupyter notebooks,

00:25:46.560 --> 00:25:48.359
we'd love to talk to you at the Posit booth.

00:25:52.160 --> 00:25:56.520
Next, we'll talk about letting little things have big impact.

00:25:56.520 --> 00:26:01.160
So sometimes a tool can kind of feel like death by 1,000 paper cuts.

00:26:01.160 --> 00:26:05.959
Each tiny drop of improvement is a sort of healing solve.

00:26:05.959 --> 00:26:09.959
If you've ever, I know when I was learning Pandas, every single time

00:26:09.959 --> 00:26:13.199
that I tried to do a join, I would have to go to the documentation

00:26:13.199 --> 00:26:16.400
because it just didn't quite feel ergonomic to me,

00:26:16.400 --> 00:26:20.619
coming from a more SQL-y or R background.

00:26:20.619 --> 00:26:24.640
And I was just like, oh, I wish I could remember this a little bit better.

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:27.439
And I think this is a really cool way to think about,

00:26:27.439 --> 00:26:29.959
how can we find these little things that can

00:26:29.959 --> 00:26:33.640
make a big impact in our projects?

00:26:33.640 --> 00:26:35.880
So we have to do the painful things, and we have

00:26:35.880 --> 00:26:37.560
to do the painful things more often.

00:26:37.560 --> 00:26:39.640
And it's funny because there's two big things that

00:26:39.640 --> 00:26:41.880
happen when you do these painful things.

00:26:41.880 --> 00:26:46.079
One, you either get really good at doing hard things,

00:26:46.079 --> 00:26:52.000
or you discover a new way to make the hard thing a little bit easier.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:55.119
So one thing that was small but really annoying

00:26:55.119 --> 00:27:00.599
was, if you've ever used an IDE and you're running just a regular script,

00:27:00.599 --> 00:27:04.119
and you click this little Play button, and it'll either run it in the terminal

00:27:04.119 --> 00:27:08.199
or in Positron, you can also run it in the console.

00:27:08.199 --> 00:27:11.219
And 99% of the time, that's super great.

00:27:11.219 --> 00:27:18.160
All I want is this Play button to run my Python file in my terminal.

00:27:18.160 --> 00:27:23.680
But sometimes I'm building a Streamlit app, or a Dash app, or Shiny app,

00:27:23.680 --> 00:27:26.920
or a FastAPI, or Flask, or whatever.

00:27:26.920 --> 00:27:31.599
And when you click that button, it actually just runs the Python file.

00:27:31.599 --> 00:27:34.199
It doesn't actually start the application.

00:27:34.199 --> 00:27:36.859
I know some people have changed their API because of this,

00:27:36.859 --> 00:27:39.000
because it's kind of annoying.

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:42.540
But something that we built in that we thought was interesting

00:27:42.540 --> 00:27:48.300
was that, when you press the button, it actually runs Streamlit, run app,

00:27:48.300 --> 00:27:52.859
in your terminal, rather than just running the Python file itself.

00:27:52.859 --> 00:27:57.660
So this is something that it's a small, small change.

00:27:57.660 --> 00:28:01.380
But if you think about people who have used this package,

00:28:01.380 --> 00:28:05.739
or people who are reading your reports, or something like that,

00:28:05.739 --> 00:28:07.979
you can think about, what are things that people say,

00:28:07.979 --> 00:28:10.140
oh, I have to click a couple times for?

00:28:10.140 --> 00:28:11.660
And maybe it's not even a complaint.

00:28:11.660 --> 00:28:13.260
It's just an observation.

00:28:13.260 --> 00:28:16.540
Being able to minimize those small paper cuts

00:28:16.540 --> 00:28:19.739
really makes a big impact time over time.

00:28:25.459 --> 00:28:30.699
Our final way of having a soft skill is to explain your work.

00:28:30.699 --> 00:28:35.140
So the idea of a rubber duck is very popular in programming.

00:28:35.140 --> 00:28:40.339
You have this little companion that you can sit there and talk to.

00:28:40.339 --> 00:28:42.739
And oftentimes, when you're talking through your problems,

00:28:42.739 --> 00:28:46.780
your solutions just kind of fall out on their own.

00:28:46.780 --> 00:28:49.660
So here's the thing that happens when you explain things.

00:28:49.660 --> 00:28:54.300
Also from our Zen of Python, if the implementation is hard to explain,

00:28:54.300 --> 00:28:55.939
it's a bad idea.

00:28:55.939 --> 00:28:58.780
So of course, being able to write documentation and things

00:28:58.780 --> 00:29:01.300
like that is helpful for the handoff of work

00:29:01.300 --> 00:29:03.099
when you're collaborating with others.

00:29:03.099 --> 00:29:07.180
But selfishly, oftentimes, when you're explaining your work,

00:29:07.180 --> 00:29:12.020
you kind of are able to figure out what is a good idea and what isn't.

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:13.979
Having clarity on the code that you're writing

00:29:13.979 --> 00:29:17.180
is really able to help you supercharge your own ability

00:29:17.180 --> 00:29:20.219
to comprehend the problems that you're solving

00:29:20.219 --> 00:29:24.739
and then build whatever you would like later.

00:29:24.739 --> 00:29:27.339
This is something that I saw on Blue Sky.

00:29:27.339 --> 00:29:29.900
I don't know if you call this a tweet or not.

00:29:29.900 --> 00:29:33.699
But on Blue Sky, I think about this almost every single day.

00:29:33.699 --> 00:29:37.540
If your writing helps even one person, it's worth doing,

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:40.540
especially if that one person is you.

00:29:40.540 --> 00:29:42.540
And of course, like the original context of this

00:29:42.540 --> 00:29:45.339
is literary people wanting to become an author.

00:29:45.339 --> 00:29:50.459
But I think of this all the time when I'm looking for a new package to use.

00:29:50.459 --> 00:29:55.699
I want to see, is there not only API documentation, that reference page,

00:29:55.699 --> 00:29:57.900
but is there a getting started guide?

00:29:57.900 --> 00:30:01.380
Are there examples or some sort of a gallery?

00:30:01.380 --> 00:30:06.339
I also think about this when I'm writing functions for myself or for others.

00:30:06.339 --> 00:30:10.660
Things like doc strings and types, it's not mandatory in Python.

00:30:10.660 --> 00:30:15.780
You can run wild, make the craziest wild west of functions you desire.

00:30:15.780 --> 00:30:19.500
But when you add types and doc strings to your functions,

00:30:19.500 --> 00:30:24.219
you can realize, oh, this doesn't make too much sense.

00:30:24.219 --> 00:30:27.099
This argument is just like the other one.

00:30:27.099 --> 00:30:29.859
Or maybe you're like me, and sometimes you add types

00:30:29.859 --> 00:30:32.619
and realize your scope is way too broad.

00:30:32.619 --> 00:30:37.619
And it also helps yourself, but it helps your users as well later

00:30:37.619 --> 00:30:40.939
to pick up this information and say, oh, I should

00:30:40.939 --> 00:30:42.780
be passing a pandas data frame here.

00:30:42.780 --> 00:30:45.380
I should be doing whatever.

00:30:45.380 --> 00:30:52.420
So writing down your intent is super important, even if it's just for yourself.

00:30:52.420 --> 00:30:56.260
And the hard part can be surfacing this information later.

00:30:56.260 --> 00:31:01.900
One more thing that I want to focus on is this help pane in Positron.

00:31:01.900 --> 00:31:04.180
So if you just write something in the console

00:31:04.180 --> 00:31:07.979
and put a little question mark next to it, it will pull up this pane,

00:31:07.979 --> 00:31:11.660
and it will render all of your doc strings.

00:31:11.660 --> 00:31:14.540
And it has syntax, not really syntax highlighting,

00:31:14.540 --> 00:31:19.900
but formatting, rich API formatting for your NumPy and your Sphinx

00:31:19.900 --> 00:31:23.219
and your epitext formatted doc strings.

00:31:23.219 --> 00:31:27.380
If you're linking to other functions, all of your documentation is interlinked.

00:31:27.380 --> 00:31:31.579
So it's helpful because you don't have to go all the way over to something

00:31:31.579 --> 00:31:35.180
like a doc site if you're just looking for something really quickly.

00:31:35.180 --> 00:31:39.459
You can also do this in Jupyter and IPython if you do double question marks.

00:31:42.979 --> 00:31:47.060
So it's really helping to get this information closer to users,

00:31:47.060 --> 00:31:54.780
even if that user is just you, to really close this feedback loop.

00:31:54.416 --> 00:32:00.976
to close this feedback loop between writing documentation and being able to use it again

00:32:00.976 --> 00:32:05.536
later. And docs, like, they're a good place to write things down, especially when it's

00:32:06.096 --> 00:32:08.176
specific to a certain function.

00:32:04.800 --> 00:32:06.240
a good place to write things down,

00:32:06.240 --> 00:32:10.600
especially when it's specific to a certain function.

00:32:10.600 --> 00:32:13.760
But oftentimes, I'll have half-baked ideas or ideas

00:32:13.760 --> 00:32:18.680
that don't quite fit into the types or a doc string.

00:32:18.680 --> 00:32:21.000
Sometimes these are my half-baked ideas

00:32:21.000 --> 00:32:23.640
on architecture or something like that.

00:32:23.640 --> 00:32:27.240
And this is where I have really enjoyed using something

00:32:27.240 --> 00:32:33.800
like a Claude MD file for things that it's not good enough

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:36.919
or it's not fleshed out enough to go to a doc site.

00:32:36.919 --> 00:32:39.079
It's not going to be sent to my colleagues

00:32:39.079 --> 00:32:41.120
or anything like that, because it turns out

00:32:41.120 --> 00:32:43.360
robots are really good at completing

00:32:43.360 --> 00:32:44.399
your half-baked ideas.

00:32:47.200 --> 00:32:49.239
I think it's a great maintenance task for something

00:32:49.239 --> 00:32:52.960
that maybe it's a project you only do part of the time,

00:32:52.960 --> 00:32:55.320
and you're going to put it down and pick it back up again

00:32:55.320 --> 00:32:57.040
in six months.

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:00.439
It's a great place to write things like your architecture

00:33:00.439 --> 00:33:02.480
or the purpose of a certain function

00:33:02.480 --> 00:33:05.800
or if there's any gotchas for your project,

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:07.640
and maybe even a happy path.

00:33:07.640 --> 00:33:10.759
We should always want to use this data frame,

00:33:10.759 --> 00:33:13.399
pull from this database, something like that.

00:33:13.399 --> 00:33:17.160
This is a great place to do super lightweight, very low

00:33:17.160 --> 00:33:19.759
stakes documentation.

00:33:19.759 --> 00:33:22.920
It's nice, because it doesn't have to be as polished.

00:33:22.920 --> 00:33:25.319
But if we think of the open source

00:33:25.319 --> 00:33:29.399
virtue of release early and release often,

00:33:29.399 --> 00:33:33.480
I want us to think about share early and share often.

00:33:33.480 --> 00:33:36.920
Bring these thoughts out of your brain as early as possible

00:33:36.920 --> 00:33:39.079
so you can add clarity to your work later on.

00:33:42.520 --> 00:33:44.999
So we want to think about tools really holistically,

00:33:44.999 --> 00:33:48.160
these hard skills, these soft skills.

00:33:48.160 --> 00:33:50.240
We can think about if we have this compass,

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:53.319
that it always points towards beautiful tools for ourselves

00:33:53.319 --> 00:33:55.380
and for others, and always making sure

00:33:55.380 --> 00:33:57.560
that we're choosing the right tools for us

00:33:57.560 --> 00:34:01.439
to live our best lives as data practitioners.

00:34:01.439 --> 00:34:05.759
We want to consider the input and the output of our work

00:34:05.759 --> 00:34:09.719
and take on as much complexity as we can as a builder

00:34:09.719 --> 00:34:13.559
to make a user's life easier.

00:34:13.559 --> 00:34:15.400
There's a lot of feedback loops, especially

00:34:15.400 --> 00:34:19.160
when you're building projects, where people are using

00:34:19.160 --> 00:34:21.719
the tools you're building, noticing pain points

00:34:21.719 --> 00:34:23.439
and sharing them with others.

00:34:23.439 --> 00:34:26.439
And this is how our ecosystem improves.

00:34:26.439 --> 00:34:29.760
We're all both consumers and contributors.

00:34:29.760 --> 00:34:31.079
And everyone's unique perspective

00:34:31.079 --> 00:34:33.579
is really important as they bring in a different way

00:34:33.579 --> 00:34:37.999
that they're traversing through this space.

00:34:37.999 --> 00:34:40.719
So building tools, it's not about this final destination

00:34:40.719 --> 00:34:45.400
of the perfect package, the perfect report.

00:34:45.400 --> 00:34:48.160
It's this journey that really never ends.

00:34:48.160 --> 00:34:52.359
Using tools reveals what's needed and what to build next.

00:34:52.359 --> 00:34:55.520
Building reveals what's possible,

00:34:55.520 --> 00:34:57.520
what we can build for others.

00:34:57.520 --> 00:35:02.079
And sharing really just starts this cycle anew.

00:35:02.079 --> 00:35:04.919
So every great tool starts as someone's story

00:35:04.919 --> 00:35:07.199
of triumph or frustration.

00:35:07.199 --> 00:35:09.320
So all of your blog posts and your conference

00:35:09.320 --> 00:35:12.079
talks, your GitHub issues that you're opening,

00:35:12.079 --> 00:35:14.600
your LinkedIn posts that you're sharing,

00:35:14.600 --> 00:35:18.800
sharing what works and what doesn't helps everyone improve.

00:35:18.800 --> 00:35:21.439
So I would really encourage, give feedback

00:35:21.439 --> 00:35:23.419
because it matters.

00:35:23.419 --> 00:35:26.419
Your tools make other people's work better.

00:35:26.419 --> 00:35:30.139
And your feedback makes our tools better.

00:35:30.139 --> 00:35:31.699
So what makes tools stick?

00:35:31.699 --> 00:35:34.380
There's the hard skills of modularity,

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:37.139
reproducibility, flexibility.

00:35:37.139 --> 00:35:39.900
There's also the soft skills of knowing your users

00:35:39.900 --> 00:35:44.960
and emphasizing discoverability, building little things

00:35:44.960 --> 00:35:48.020
for big impact, and explaining your work.

00:35:48.020 --> 00:35:50.339
This is all driven by a mission for people

00:35:50.339 --> 00:35:52.540
to have the most beautiful experience

00:35:52.540 --> 00:35:54.660
with the open source tools that they're using

00:35:54.660 --> 00:35:59.339
and for people to feel empowered that they can build tools

00:35:59.339 --> 00:36:02.260
small, medium, or large.

00:36:02.260 --> 00:36:03.740
So thank you all.

