Sure.

00:39:20.800 --> 00:39:23.120
So my question is, one of the things you do

00:39:23.120 --> 00:39:26.359
is you build a lot of features for the IDE

00:39:26.359 --> 00:39:29.240
or in the process of building small little tools into it.

00:39:29.240 --> 00:39:33.400
And what I wonder about is, what kind of signals or feedback

00:39:33.400 --> 00:39:36.000
do you use to figure out if this feature that you've just added

00:39:36.000 --> 00:39:37.400
was actually a good idea or not?

00:39:37.400 --> 00:39:39.440
Because I mean, looking at my own experience,

00:39:39.440 --> 00:39:41.000
like building a new feature, you probably

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:42.800
think it's a good idea, which is why you release it.

00:39:42.800 --> 00:39:44.359
But that doesn't mean that your users actually

00:39:44.359 --> 00:39:45.879
agree with your enthusiasm.

00:39:45.879 --> 00:39:47.599
So how do you go about figuring that out?

00:39:47.599 --> 00:39:52.319
Yeah, the question is, you get a lot of feedback from people,

00:39:52.319 --> 00:39:53.639
and we build a lot of features.

00:39:53.639 --> 00:39:55.720
So how do we decide if, one, a feature is needed,

00:39:55.720 --> 00:39:58.159
and two, if not only is it needed,

00:39:58.159 --> 00:40:00.199
but people actually want it, which are subtly

00:40:00.199 --> 00:40:03.319
different things?

00:40:03.319 --> 00:40:05.280
I think one thing, we're lucky enough

00:40:05.280 --> 00:40:09.479
we have an active online community of people

00:40:09.479 --> 00:40:13.759
who are willing to tell us, I want you to support x, y,

00:40:13.759 --> 00:40:15.400
and z.

00:40:15.400 --> 00:40:17.800
So I think that is one way.

00:40:17.800 --> 00:40:23.400
And another is the intuition of, because we know our users,

00:40:23.400 --> 00:40:26.120
I think of, I was really struggling

00:40:26.120 --> 00:40:29.280
with deploying Jupyter Notebooks,

00:40:29.280 --> 00:40:32.840
or I was really struggling with transferring from this data

00:40:32.840 --> 00:40:34.599
science library to this one.

00:40:34.599 --> 00:40:38.519
So being able to infuse our own knowledge of knowing the users

00:40:38.519 --> 00:40:40.880
is also a good place to start.

00:40:40.880 --> 00:40:44.200
I think asking questions is super reasonable,

00:40:44.200 --> 00:40:47.039
saying, hey, I'm thinking about this.

00:40:47.039 --> 00:40:48.919
Is this something that would work?

00:40:48.919 --> 00:40:52.479
Is this something that makes sense from your stakeholders?

00:40:52.479 --> 00:40:54.159
Closing this feedback loop and not

00:40:54.159 --> 00:40:57.800
being afraid to just say, early on,

00:40:57.800 --> 00:41:00.599
can we have feedback on this, even if it's as a prototype

00:41:00.599 --> 00:41:02.680
or something like that.

00:41:02.680 --> 00:41:04.599
So a lot of communication with users

00:41:04.599 --> 00:41:07.159
and trying to put yourself in their shoes

00:41:07.159 --> 00:41:10.240
for small, medium, and large features.

