00:41:14.200 --> 00:41:16.120
Isabel, I have a question.

00:41:16.120 --> 00:41:21.680
How do you encourage data science persona types

00:41:21.680 --> 00:41:23.320
to become tool builders?

00:41:26.200 --> 00:41:27.760
And the reason I'm asking this is

00:41:27.760 --> 00:41:31.560
because sometimes there's this psychological barrier

00:41:31.560 --> 00:41:32.919
to building tools.

00:41:32.919 --> 00:41:34.599
They're like, I'm a tool consumer.

00:41:34.599 --> 00:41:36.440
I do not want to build.

00:41:36.440 --> 00:41:37.760
I just want to use the tools.

00:41:37.760 --> 00:41:39.120
I just want to get my job done.

00:41:41.640 --> 00:41:43.880
Yeah, I'd like to hear some of your thoughts on that.

00:41:43.880 --> 00:41:45.839
The question is, how do you convince

00:41:45.839 --> 00:41:49.320
people who identify as a tool consumer to be a tool builder?

00:41:51.719 --> 00:41:54.200
There's a couple different ways that we can talk about this.

00:41:54.200 --> 00:41:58.800
I think one is, the time is now, because of the AI tools

00:41:58.800 --> 00:42:00.839
that are available, I think the barrier

00:42:00.839 --> 00:42:03.000
to starting to build a Python package, like I said,

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:04.240
is way lower.

00:42:04.240 --> 00:42:07.279
You can say, I have these functions,

00:42:07.279 --> 00:42:10.159
literally copy and paste them into ChatGBT or Cloud

00:42:10.159 --> 00:42:11.880
or whatever, and be like, hey, can you

00:42:11.880 --> 00:42:14.279
make this into a Python package?

00:42:14.279 --> 00:42:17.959
I think data scientists love reproducibility.

00:42:17.959 --> 00:42:20.800
So if you can frame things in a reproducible way,

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:23.560
this is really important, because the more tools you

00:42:23.560 --> 00:42:26.560
build, it makes your work more reproducible

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:30.479
by having these functions that you can reuse.

00:42:30.479 --> 00:42:33.419
So I think those are two important factors.

00:42:33.419 --> 00:42:35.880
Also, the more specialized something

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:38.919
is for your task, I have this function

00:42:38.919 --> 00:42:41.440
for my specific data set, the faster

00:42:41.440 --> 00:42:43.200
they're going to be able to work.

00:42:43.200 --> 00:42:45.640
So even if it's just a small incremental tool

00:42:45.640 --> 00:42:48.680
of changing your script that you run all of your data

00:42:48.719 --> 00:42:51.359
through into a function, like, congratulations,

00:42:51.359 --> 00:42:52.899
you've already become a tool builder.

00:42:52.899 --> 00:42:55.800
You're already taking steps onto this path.

00:42:55.800 --> 00:42:59.519
So I think the time is right to change our mindsets

00:42:59.519 --> 00:43:02.719
and just be a little bit of a tool builder as long as well

00:43:02.719 --> 00:43:05.599
as being a tool consumer.

00:43:05.599 --> 00:43:07.839
All right, I'll take one more, or that's it?

